Mr Martin would even drive her to hair appointments, run errands, cook for her and take her to hospital.

She was tough and stubborn and would test Mr Martin, but he could be too and did not stop looking after her.

'All she wanted to do was live and die in her house, and that seems like a pretty simple request. And all she really needed was some help using her hands and being on her feet,' he said. 

Ms Macefield, a very private person, did not like the worldwide attention she received for just wanting to stay put in her home.

She stood her ground not because she was standing up to corporate America or because she wanted to be a hero. She simply didn't want to leave.

'Some people still believe that she was doing it to stand up against the man, and that really wasn't it. 

'She decided what it was she wanted to do and stuck to her guns, and that part to me makes sense. That's what I relate to,' said Mr Martin.

