The story of the house came at the end of a remarkable life according to stories she told Mr Martin, some of which he was able to corroborate through letters and photographs he found after her death.

Ms Macefield had a large musical collection, and played the clarinet. She talked of playing with jazz and swing musician Benny Goodman, her cousin, and his friends Jimmy and Tommy Dorsey.

She had lived overseas in her early life, could quote from classic books, and spoke multiple languages.

She also claimed to have worked as a spy during World War II, until she was captured and sent to the concentration camp at Dachau, from which she then escaped.

Later she ran an orphanage for war refugees before returning to America to look after her mother.

Despite shunning the limelight she has been immortalized in Seattle due to her refusal of the developer's money.

Some two dozen people are reported to have tattoos of her house; a drink is named after her at a local cocktail bar; and the Macefield music festival still attracts a crowd of 3,000 people each year.

